@page
@model McpViaApimModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Use the MCP server through Azure API Management";
    ViewData["Description"] = "Learn how to expose the Office Versions MCP endpoint through Azure API Management and call it from AI clients or custom integrations.";
}

<div class="container">
    <div class="privacy-header">
        <div class="privacy-header-icon">
            <i class="bi bi-cloud-arrow-up"></i>
        </div>
        <h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>
        <p>Expose the Office Versions MCP endpoint behind Azure API Management and keep the backend routing simple.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-lg-12">
            <div class="privacy-container">
                <div class="privacy-section">
                    <h2><i class="bi bi-info-circle me-2"></i>Overview</h2>
                    <p>
                        The Office Versions site already exposes an HTTP-based MCP endpoint at <code>/mcp</code>.
                        Azure API Management can be used as the public entry point so you can add authentication,
                        throttling, observability, and versioning without changing the backend implementation.
                    </p>
                    <div class="alert alert-info" role="alert">
                        <i class="bi bi-lightbulb me-2"></i>
                        <strong>Tip:</strong> the OpenAPI definition for import is available at <a href="/swagger/v1/mcp-openapi.json" target="_blank">/swagger/v1/mcp-openapi.json</a>.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="privacy-section">
                    <h2><i class="bi bi-list-ol me-2"></i>Recommended setup</h2>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Create a new API in Azure API Management.</li>
                        <li>Import the MCP OpenAPI definition from <code>/swagger/v1/mcp-openapi.json</code>.</li>
                        <li>Configure the backend URL to the App Service host that serves the website.</li>
                        <li>Set the API route so that requests to the APIM endpoint are forwarded to <code>/mcp</code> on the backend.</li>
                        <li>Apply authentication and policies in APIM according to your environment requirements.</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>

                <div class="privacy-section">
                    <h2><i class="bi bi-sliders me-2"></i>APIM configuration example</h2>
                    <p>
                        A simple APIM configuration looks like this:
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>API name:</strong> OfficeVersions MCP</li>
                        <li><strong>API URL suffix:</strong> <code>mcp</code></li>
                        <li><strong>Web service URL:</strong> <code>https://&lt;your-app-service-host&gt;</code></li>
                        <li><strong>Operations:</strong> <code>GET /mcp</code> and <code>POST /mcp</code></li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>
                        If your APIM API uses a base path, make sure the backend request still targets the original MCP route.
                        In practice this means forwarding the request path to <code>/mcp</code> rather than dropping it.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="privacy-section">
                    <h2><i class="bi bi-terminal me-2"></i>Example calls</h2>
                    <p>Once the API is published, you can invoke it using the APIM hostname.</p>

                    <pre><code>curl https://&lt;apim-hostname&gt;/mcp</code></pre>
                    <pre><code>curl -X POST https://&lt;apim-hostname&gt;/mcp \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"jsonrpc":"2.0","id":1,"method":"tools/list"}'</code></pre>

                    <p>
                        If your APIM instance expects a subscription key or OAuth token, include the relevant header in the request.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="privacy-section">
                    <h2><i class="bi bi-shield-check me-2"></i>Security and operational notes</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Protect the public endpoint with subscription keys, OAuth, or IP restrictions.</li>
                        <li>Use APIM policies to add rate limiting and logging for MCP traffic.</li>
                        <li>Keep the backend route at <code>/mcp</code> so the OpenAPI definition remains aligned with the implementation.</li>
                        <li>Monitor the APIM and backend logs to confirm that JSON-RPC requests are being forwarded correctly.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

@section Scripts {
    <style>
        pre {
            background-color: var(--bs-gray-100, #f8f9fa);
            border-radius: 0.5rem;
            padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
            overflow-x: auto;
        }

        code {
            font-size: 0.95rem;
        }
    </style>
}
